english:
  title: Imperial Edict Rewarding the Meritorious Service of the Prince of Suhan
  author: Yu Seong-won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Thus speaks the King:

    Heaven brings forth the virtuous for the sake of the realm, and this is bound to the cosmic order. The ruler grants rank and land to proclaim his mandate, thereby honoring those of true merit. Following the eternal principles, I make known these rewards.

    My esteemed Uncle embodied the essence of heaven, earth, and the luminaries. He refined his integrity through wind and frost alike. His bearing was majestic and profound, his resolve unshakeable and stern. Filial piety and fraternal love flowed from his very nature; loyalty and righteousness sprang from his sincere heart. He possessed the talents of heroes and the learning of sages. His spirit encompassed an age; his courage led all armies. Among kinsmen, his virtue commanded respect; at court, his presence inspired reverence. In goodness he found his greatest joy, unmoved by wealth or sensual pleasure. In serving his sovereign, he remained steadfast through ease and hardship alike—never wavering in his integrity. He stood firm as the nation's bulwark, steadfast as virtue itself.

    I, a youth of tender years, encountered calamity in my house. Seeking to overcome these tribulations, I entrusted governance to my ministers, hoping for their support to restore prosperity and peace. Yet at that very time, the Prince Yeong, occupying the station of my closest relative, harbored thoughts of usurpation. He believed that with my youth and inexperience, the throne might fall to his scheming. He distributed favors lavishly, courted popular acclaim, and drew lesser men to his private faction. Over long years, he nurtured his treacherous designs.

    The traitorous officials—Hwangbo In, Kim Jong-seo, Yi Yang, Min Shin, Jo Geuk-kwan, and their ilk—forgot the benevolence with which they had been favored. They conspired in shadows to bring ruin upon the state, forming secret alliances, gathering followers. They scorned my youth, usurped my authority, wielded power for private gain, and sold imperial favors. Officials were appointed through kinship and bribery ran rampant. Taxes grew burdensome; construction exhausted our treasury. They obscured my wisdom, blocked the flow of my virtue. The public good dimmed as private interest flooded forth like torrents. Heaven's anger rose above while I remained blind; the people's resentment swelled below while I failed to perceive it.

    My Uncle once, pained by these wrongs, raised his voice in remonstrance—yet I, in my ignorance, paid him little heed. So thoroughly had treachery entrenched itself around the Prince that the court itself became corrupted. As their conspiracy deepened, they gathered nightly in secret, communicating with palace eunuchs to monitor developments, while externally they conspired with generals and garrison commanders, fixing times and dates for their rising. Their faction swelled; their power grew daily. The great conspiracy took root so firmly that it could not be extracted, and I stood isolated and powerless. The fate of the realm hung by a thread.

    My Uncle, gifted with foresight, burned with righteous indignation. Knowing that Heaven and Earth could not abide such evil, caring not for his own life when the realm's survival was at stake, he resolved upon decisive action. With bold strategy and brilliant wisdom, he rallied the loyal and true, swept away the treacherous crew in a single stroke. The court rejoiced; the people celebrated in the streets. The tottering realm grew stable once more; the divine mandate, nearly lost, was restored. This was achieved through unwavering purpose and profound devotion—sincerity that moved even spirits, loyalty inscribed upon sun and moon. Thus in mere moments, the conspiracy was severed; before a single day had passed, clarity returned.

    His deeds shine resplendent, surpassing all ages. Without my Uncle, how could I have endured? Truly, it was the hidden blessing of Heaven, Earth, and our ancestors that, working through my Uncle's hand, brought peace to the realm. If his birth were not written in the cosmic order itself, how could such a thing be possible?

    Therefore, I have exalted his loyalty, granting him both military command and civil authority. I have laid bare my heart in trusting him; he, in turn, has exhausted himself in service. He spread the benevolent grace of imperial rule and reformed all corruptions of treacherous officials. Without raising his voice or drawing his blade, he established the realm upon firm foundations and brought the people to live in peace. Though he has become the nation's pillar upon which all rely, he remains humble in bearing. Though his merit spans the heavens, he practices constant self-effacement. Truly, he is the worthy minister to whom I may entrust my heir and upon whom the realm may depend.

    In ancient times, the Duke of Zhou eliminated traitors to stabilize the royal house—a great righteousness that shines through all ages. Comparing present to past, though the age differs, the parallel remains perfect.

    Therefore, I establish him as Merit Subject of the First Rank in the Pacification, granting him the title of "He Who Musters Loyalty and Wields Righteousness to Stabilize the Realm and Preserve the Dynasty, Determining Strategy in Pacification." I grant him:

    One thousand households in his enfeoffed domain; five hundred households from which he shall receive actual revenue; six hundred measures of annual stipend; six hundred slaves; five hundred lots of farmland; twenty-five taels of gold; one hundred taels of silver; four horses with fine saddles; ten bolts of fine silk; five bolts each of gauze and damask; one ceremonial robe; one rhinoceros-horn belt; satin cap, ceremonial hat, boots, and other items of honor.

    His merit is vast; my rewards are meager. Yet what does he desire? For my part, I feel them insufficient. I beg him to accept these offerings as tokens of my utmost sincerity.

    Alas! My Uncle possesses the excellent talents of the Duke of Zhou and has achieved his great merit besides. I, meanwhile, find myself in the tender years of a young king, facing trials such as young kings must endure. As I have entrusted to him what was once entrusted to the Duke of Zhou, so must he now support me as the Duke once supported his sovereign. When above and below work in concert, what impediment could prevent our success? I gaze upon your unwavering loyalty with deep reliance. Therefore I issue this edict for your full understanding.
  footnotes:
    - The 'cosmic order' (氣數) was a classical concept suggesting that the rise and fall of dynasties and the emergence of virtuous individuals were determined by patterns in heaven and earth.
    - The comparison to the Duke of Zhou and King Cheng of the Zhou dynasty is a classical reference emphasizing the parallels between this historical moment and ancient precedent—a common rhetorical device in Korean royal edicts.
    - 'The gifts enumerated at the conclusion represent both material reward and symbolic honor: land revenue, stipends, slaves, farmland, precious metals, horses, and fine garments—the traditional marks of highest noble rank.'
